Performance evaluation for machine problem 4:

	First Fit:
	*coalesce disabled - took 3.18 seconds to run the driver with other settings default.
			   - 46271 items in list after exercise
			   - 47539 items in list after clean up
	*coalesce enabled  - took 0.15 seconds to run with identical settings otherwise
			   - 636 items in list
			   - 2 items in list after clean up
	*From this, it seems pretty clear that the coalescence is significantly 
		better for speed performance and for fragmentation.
	
	Best Fit:
	*coalesce disabled - took 1.07 seconds to run the driver with other settings default.
			   - 7649 items in list after exercise
			   - 8917 items in list after clean up
	*coalesce enabled  - took 0.16 seconds to run with identical settings otherwise
			   - 320 items in list
			   - 2 items in list after clean up
	*Here, we can see that the best fit policy results in half the amount of 
		fragmentation that the first fit does, with only a .01 second 
		time difference.
	When assessing the first fit versus best fit policies, we can see that the fragmentation is much 
worse in the first fit policy and the speed gained from using the first fit is very small. Coalescence 
may take time to combine the units, but due to the roving point being placed on the coalesced block, 
there is a good chance that the pointer will find the memory it needs in the list and not have to make 
another call to the operating system. This vastly improves speed and would only slow down the algorithm 
if very small memory calls were asked every time. I see virtually no downsides in using it. The best fit 
is technically faster in the case where you are coalescing the memory, as the roving pointer is always on 
the coalesced block, vastly increasing the chance that the pointer is starting on the desired block and 
not having to search.
	In regards to a two-way versus one-way implementation, I would say that in some edge cases, I was
forced to loop my tailing pointer all the way around the list to grab certain blocks and if a block of
new memory was added, I always had to loop all the way around to grab it. This would have been mitigated
with a previous pointer built into the structure, but this would increase the amount of memory being used
flatly across the board by increasing the unit size. This would also marginally increase the time it took
to swap out different block and could lead to chain errors. Lastly, you would also need to be sure to 
clear out the previous pointer in allocated blocks to prevent snooping from users. All in all, if I had 
to do it again, I probably would have used a two-way list instead of the default one-way.
